amilies depended on selling such goods. When factories eliminated the economic value of handwork, footbinding died out. As the last generation of footbound women passes away, Bound Feet, Young Hands presents a data-driven examination of the social and economic aspects of this misunderstood custom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFootbindingxChina. 0aFootbindingxEconomic aspectsxChina. 0aHandicraft industriesxChina. 0aRural girlsxEmploymentxChina. 0aRural girlsxSocial life and customsxChina. 0aRural womenxEmploymentxChina. 0aRural womenxSocial life and customsxChina. 4aChina. 4acotton. 4aeconomic history. 4afootbinding. 4ahand labor. 4aindustrialization. 4alabor. 4atextile industry. 4atwentieth-century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aGates, Hill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503601079zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601079.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles